A sustainable fashion designer is using a real symmetric matrix A to represent the carbon footprint of different materials used in their clothing line. The matrix A is 3x3 and is given as follows:

A = [2, 4, 1;
     4, 3, 5;
     1, 5, 6]

The designer wants to find the eigenvalues and the corresponding eigenvectors of the matrix to understand the effect of each material on the carbon footprint. 

Calculate the eigenvalues and the eigenvectors of the matrix A.

The interior designer is tasked with creating a unique pattern to place eco-friendly tiles on a large, rectangular hotel lobby floor. The designer decides to use two types of square tiles, each with sides of length 1 unit. The first type of tile is made from recycled glass, while the second type is made from reclaimed wood. 

The designer arranges the tiles in a pattern that starts from one corner of the lobby and spreads outwards. The design starts with a 1 by 1 square made from the glass tile, then a 2 by 2 square made from wood tiles is added around it, then a 3 by 3 square made from glass tiles is added around the 2 by 2 square and so on, alternating between glass and wood. 

The lobby has a total area of $n^2$, for some positive integer $n$. The designer wants to know how many of each type of tile she will use. 

Let $f(n)$ be the number of glass tiles and $g(n)$ be the number of wooden tiles used when the total area is $n^2$.

(a) Prove that for all positive integers $n$, $f(n)$ and $g(n)$ are given by:
\[f(n) = \left\{
	\begin{array}{ll}
		\frac{n(n + 1)(2n + 1)}{6}  & \mbox{if } n \mbox{ is even} \\
		\frac{(n + 1)^2(n)}{3} & \mbox{if } n \mbox{ is odd}
	\end{array}
\right.\]
\[g(n) = \left\{
	\begin{array}{ll}
		\frac{(n + 1)^2(n)}{3} & \mbox{if } n \mbox{ is even} \\
		\frac{n(n + 1)(2n + 1)}{6}  & \mbox{if } n \mbox{ is odd}
	\end{array}
\right.\]

(b) Find all $n$ such that $f(n) = g(n)$.
